So I wanted to start off talking
about the great momentum we

00:00:55.380 --> 00:00:56.820
have on Google Play.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:59.000
And it's pretty exciting,
because right now,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.250
the last number we released--
and this was a long time

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:04.180
ago-- talked about over one
billion activated Android

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:05.349
devices.

00:01:05.349 --> 00:01:09.090
And the other thing we know is
that three in four, in fact,

00:01:09.090 --> 00:01:13.370
over three in four
Android users play games.

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:19.570
So this is just an
incredible opportunity

00:01:19.570 --> 00:01:21.670
to grow an engaged
audience for your game.

00:01:21.670 --> 00:01:24.050
But here is something
even cooler.

00:01:24.050 --> 00:01:26.540
In the last six months
on Google Play games,

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:30.970
we've added over 75
million new users.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.470
So rapidly, rapidly
growing audience

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:37.720
base that's very, very
engaged with gaming content.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:40.030
So what is Google Play games?

00:01:40.030 --> 00:01:42.690
All right, so we have
Achievements, Leaderboards,

00:01:42.690 --> 00:01:45.200
Cloud Save, and Multiplayer.

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:46.810
All the basic stuff
you would need.

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:49.300
Multiplayer we actually
have both real time

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:51.870
and turn-based multiplayer.

00:01:51.870 --> 00:01:53.780
And these are all
things that we've

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:58.060
proven to be really
valuable for gamers.

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.270
So there's much
more to this network

00:02:01.270 --> 00:02:03.750
though, than just a
collection of game services.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:07.040
Ultimately, Play Games
is a concentrated network

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:09.410
of people who enjoy games.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:12.350
In an ecosystem this large, it's
essential to bring the people

00:02:12.350 --> 00:02:16.206
together and help you
connect them to your content.

00:02:16.206 --> 00:02:18.080
For those of you who
have adopted Play Games,

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:21.210
we review the data
that you've given us,

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:25.952
and we've come up with these
kinds of basic statistics.

00:02:25.952 --> 00:02:27.660
We're talking about
high quality players.

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:32.420
We're talking about people who
are playing longer, more often,

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:34.370
and are more likely to monetize.

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:38.010
So again, Google Play
users fit this profile.

00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:40.440
That's what we see
time and time again.

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:43.090
Now whether this is correlation
or causation is unclear,

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:46.590
but people who sign into Games
fit these characteristics.

00:02:46.590 --> 00:02:49.170
They are your best game players.

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:52.010
But the question is, how do
you engage these players?

00:02:52.010 --> 00:02:53.520
With such a diverse
audience, it's

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.700
important to think about
the thematics of your title

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:58.790
and who it resonates with, and
what type of engagement appeals

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:00.900
to them.

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:03.420
So one way to think about
engaging your audience

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:05.850
is, how open they are
to social interaction.

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:11.490
And which techniques are useful
for different gaming personas.

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:15.299
Here at Android labs, we've
done extensive research.

00:03:15.299 --> 00:03:17.090
Which leads us to the
conclusion that there

00:03:17.090 --> 00:03:20.000
are three fundamental
gamer archetypes.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:20.930
We actually did this.

00:03:20.930 --> 00:03:22.580
This is seriously
research that we did,

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:23.746
and we actually had a study.

00:03:23.746 --> 00:03:26.440
And we've named these
things multiple things,

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.750
but I like to refer to them as
the competitor, the achiever,

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:31.940
and the stealth gamer.

00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:34.810
And you can plot these
on a graph-- again,

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:38.930
this is a highly scientific
study-- based upon openness.

00:03:38.930 --> 00:03:41.790
So we have our least open
gamer to our most open gamer,

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:46.480
in terms of being open
to social interaction.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:50.150
At the open end of our scale,
the competitor archetype

00:03:50.150 --> 00:03:51.630
engages in everything.

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:54.050
Achievements, Leaderboards,
and Multiplayer.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:57.160
They thrive in competitive and
deep cooperative experiences.

00:03:57.160 --> 00:03:59.570
They own every console,
their personal home page

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:01.760
lists their achievements.

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:03.880
They play games on mobile
for the same reason

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:06.990
that Captain Kirk climbed
mountains in Star Trek four,

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:09.500
because they are there.

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:12.740
Achiever is on the other side
of the openness spectrum.

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:15.300
They thrive in progression,
solving problems,

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:16.476
revealing story.

00:04:16.476 --> 00:04:18.809
But they don't really want
to play in social situations.

00:04:18.809 --> 00:04:20.211
They're like OK, hold on.

00:04:20.211 --> 00:04:22.210
This is the mobile
equivalent of the people that

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:24.310
work to earn a million
points in geometry wars

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:27.057
without dying, just to
get the final achievement.

00:04:27.057 --> 00:04:28.515
The people who
played Final Fantasy

00:04:28.515 --> 00:04:31.930
VIII to get the two-minute
long Eden animation.

00:04:31.930 --> 00:04:33.900
Yes, like the
competitor, these guys

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:37.440
are also looking for deeper
phone and tablet experiences.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:38.550
And this is our third one.

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:39.883
This is kind of a funny persona.

00:04:39.883 --> 00:04:42.180
We actually refer to it
as the wolf, the stealth.

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:44.900
They're like, I'm not a gamer!

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:48.060
But they actually play
games every single day.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:50.350
And while they're
less likely to engage

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:52.050
in direct social
interaction, they

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:54.140
welcome passive interaction.

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:56.620
This means they can be
engaged to help a friend,

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:58.470
or compare themselves
to another player,

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:00.984
so long as the social
interaction is fast,

00:05:00.984 --> 00:05:02.150
and the impact is immediate.

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:08.090
So with these three
personas in mind,

00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:10.220
let's cover how
Play Games Services

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:12.460
can help you reach each of them.

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:14.890
So this guy's kind
of obvious, OK?

00:05:14.890 --> 00:05:16.130
Social Leaderboards.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:18.950
He wants to compete with
his friends, real-time

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:20.450
and turn-based multiplayer.

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:23.180
This guy's the competitor.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:25.750
So this is a game I've
been playing a lot,

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:28.750
and these scores are
actually out of date.

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:32.530
And I've been playing Smash
Hit not just because it's

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:35.980
an awesome game, but because my
friends are playing the game.

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:38.150
And I can't tell you
the countless hours

00:05:38.150 --> 00:05:40.420
I've put in, trying
to beat these scores.

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:43.400
And even with all
of that, I'm still

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:46.400
actually kind of suffering.

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:47.150
And this is great.

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:51.050
Because this is how this
engage player actually uses

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.872
their social graph to both
compete within the game,

00:05:55.872 --> 00:05:57.580
but also to reach out
to friends and say,

00:05:57.580 --> 00:05:59.210
this is an awesome game.

00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:01.350
And by the way, I love the
way this game monetizes.

00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:03.665
It actually monetizes
based upon checkpoints,

00:06:03.665 --> 00:06:04.790
which is kind of brilliant.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:06.130
So you can play the
game from the start,

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:07.570
but if you actually want
to progress in the game,

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:08.736
you actually have to buy it.

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:16.720
So real-time multiplayer is
also great for the competitor.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:19.030
All right, there
are how many games

00:06:19.030 --> 00:06:21.580
that are calling the same basic
game, sitting on Play Games

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:22.320
right now.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:25.440
But this game was set apart,
because Clumsy Bird actually

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:28.070
uses real-time auto-matching
to drive a tournament

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:29.740
system between players.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:31.660
And this encourages
and rewards them

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.100
to play together,
and more often.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:36.940
Auto-matching provides
instant access

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:38.700
to both their own
social graph, as well as

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.955
the entire set of
players that are actually

00:06:40.955 --> 00:06:41.830
playing the game now.

00:06:41.830 --> 00:06:44.390
So people get matched up
really, really quickly.

00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:46.930
But of course they also have
a way of inviting friends

00:06:46.930 --> 00:06:49.260
directly, which allows
them to not only grow

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:50.830
the players in the
game, but it also

00:06:50.830 --> 00:06:54.710
allows people to actually
grow their graph of players.

00:06:54.710 --> 00:06:56.890
And in this game, they
actually further encourage me

00:06:56.890 --> 00:06:58.810
to compare myself to others.

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:01.010
So how did my friend
beat my score?

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:03.600
And where did they get that
awesome hat for their bird?

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:08.160
And turn-based
multiplayer is another way

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:10.400
to accomplish this kind
of social interaction,

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:12.040
especially for
gameplay sessioms that

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.760
can be completed incrementally
over a course of days.

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:16.780
So in a similar way to
real-time multiplayer,

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:18.930
matches can be played
by inviting friends,

00:07:18.930 --> 00:07:21.900
or auto-picking people
who are playing right now.

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.590
And what makes the invite system
effective in encouraging repeat

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:27.480
gameplay is showing players who
you've played with recently,

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.800
or who are actively
playing the game.

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:33.070
So for example, this
person, who is not me,

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:34.910
is reminded that I
am playing the game.

00:07:34.910 --> 00:07:38.039
And yes, that is
me with long hair.

00:07:38.039 --> 00:07:39.580
And this is Frozen
Front, by the way.

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:41.544
I just want to call
out to our friends

00:07:41.544 --> 00:07:43.960
at Handy Games for putting
together an awesome [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:43.960 --> 00:07:44.459
for us.

00:07:44.459 --> 00:07:47.300
Thank you.

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:50.190
So when you receive a
notification to play a game,

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:51.755
it's an opportunity
to install a game

00:07:51.755 --> 00:07:53.310
you weren't playing previously.

00:07:53.310 --> 00:07:55.619
In the next update with
Play Games Services, which

00:07:55.619 --> 00:07:57.410
is rolling out in the
next couple of weeks,

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:01.240
we're introducing expanded
notifications for Play Games.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:03.100
And the goal of
these changes are

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:05.070
to deliver multiplayer
and other requested game

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.080
actions between users across
Google's social graph.

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:10.490
The main change that users
are notified differently,

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:13.920
based upon the priority
settings on their device.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.270
So what is actually
look like in real life?

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:18.810
Once again, using Frozen
Front as an example,

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:21.410
we've got a new
game action here.

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:25.425
And so this first
example is a game action

00:08:25.425 --> 00:08:29.490
that came in from someone who
is actually in my circles.

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:31.340
So it pops up, I can
see their picture,

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:32.840
I see everything about them.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:35.252
The second one we've actually
aggregated a game action

00:08:35.252 --> 00:08:36.835
from someone who
wasn't in my circles.

00:08:36.835 --> 00:08:38.731
These show up silently.

00:08:38.731 --> 00:08:40.814
They show up along with
the rest of notifications,

00:08:40.814 --> 00:08:42.480
you see I've got one more.

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:44.850
And then we actually
go into the screen,

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:47.230
we now have the
ability to go and add

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:49.240
this person to my circles.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:52.680
So one, you can directly
grow your game graph

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:55.157
through these invitations,
your social gaming graph

00:08:55.157 --> 00:08:56.240
through these invitations.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:58.630
And two, we actually
aggregate these

00:08:58.630 --> 00:09:01.930
in a way that's very, very
low bandwidth for the user

00:09:01.930 --> 00:09:02.855
to deal with.

00:09:02.855 --> 00:09:05.450
I think both of those are
really critical to making people

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:08.830
engage with, and
love, the service.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:12.300
So here's something that's
very near and dear to my heart.

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:14.200
And these are actually
two of my friends.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:17.510
She has an Android device,
and he has an iPhone.

00:09:17.510 --> 00:09:20.400
And they do all sorts
of things together.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.420
They send each
other text messages,

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:26.373
they send each
other emails, they

00:09:26.373 --> 00:09:27.623
can send each other snapchats.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.240
They can even make phone
calls with each other.

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:39.530
But if they actually want to
play a game together, you know,

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:40.770
it just doesn't happen.

00:09:40.770 --> 00:09:43.420
And the reason why is
that these games often

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:45.460
use services that are
not cross-platform.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:48.740
So I wanted to really
emphasize this.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:51.690
From the very start
of Google Play Games,

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:54.640
we have thought about this
as a cross-platform service.

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:57.830
We support Android,
iOS, and the web

00:09:57.830 --> 00:09:59.630
for the vast majority
of our services.

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:04.920
And we support Android and iOS
for things like multi-player.

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:09.410
Because the truth is,
both of these platforms

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:11.930
are really, really
important to our audience.

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:14.430
And what's most important
to us is making sure

00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:16.630
that our audience
gets what they want.

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:18.930
That our users are happy.

00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:24.830
So let's talk a
little bit about this.

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:27.390
So for a long time
on Android we've had,

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:30.820
and iOS, from day one we've
supported achievements,

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:32.660
Cloud Save, and Leaderboards.

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:34.390
And Cloud Save is
really, really awesome.

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:36.420
Because there are
people that have,

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:40.390
for example, an Android phone,
an iOS tablet, and vice versa.

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:41.640
And it's really, really great.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:43.473
It's almost magical to
bring that experience

00:10:43.473 --> 00:10:47.060
from one device to the other,
and just have it carry over.

00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:49.440
And but for a long
time, multiplayer

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:51.310
has been an
Android-only feature.

00:10:51.310 --> 00:10:53.540
So last week we
actually announced

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:57.810
that full-blown both turn-based
and real-time multiplayer

00:10:57.810 --> 00:10:58.980
is coming to iOS.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:03.080
And let's start with
why you should care.

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:06.970
Because in some ways, we know
this is going to be more work.

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:11.060
You have to care about
different clients being in sync.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:13.830
But for starters, it's
a really cool trick.

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:18.590
And we've been saying
forever that games

00:11:18.590 --> 00:11:20.240
are the original social.

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:21.916
I mean, this is the
right thing to do.

00:11:21.916 --> 00:11:23.540
People want to play
with their friends,

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:26.750
no matter what
devices they have.

00:11:26.750 --> 00:11:29.240
And frankly, you're going
to get a better matchmaking

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:29.910
experience.

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:33.470
I mean think about it this way,
a typical mobile multiplayer

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:37.100
set up is a peer-to-peer network
that looks kind of like this.

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:39.050
Well, I mean, with people.

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:45.010
And basically all these
people are interconnected

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:49.290
as you're playing
a real-time game.

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:51.165
But if you have fewer
players-- look around--

00:11:51.165 --> 00:11:53.260
you've got fewer options.

00:11:53.260 --> 00:11:56.300
So for example,
our system might be

00:11:56.300 --> 00:11:58.680
matching some players
in San Francisco

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:00.770
with a third player
in London, which

