00:34:13.830 --> 00:34:15.370
endpoints.

00:34:15.370 --> 00:34:16.989
We're looking to
see what we can do

00:34:16.989 --> 00:34:19.280
to bring some of
the other services.

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:21.154
Turn-based is kind
of partially there.

00:34:21.154 --> 00:34:22.820
Real-time we need to
do a bunch of work,

00:34:22.820 --> 00:34:24.530
because real-time
relies on a bunch

00:34:24.530 --> 00:34:28.790
of sophisticated networking
that we don't have really yet,

00:34:28.790 --> 00:34:31.139
in a standard way
across web browsers.

00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:34.908
But I think that we'll see
turn-based next, probably.

00:34:34.908 --> 00:34:36.949
It's still all about, how
do we get notifications

00:34:36.949 --> 00:34:38.259
in the best way to users?

00:34:38.259 --> 00:34:40.550
And making sure that experience
is really, really good.

00:34:40.550 --> 00:34:43.945
But we're very, very close
on turn-based actually.

00:34:43.945 --> 00:34:44.945
AUDIENCE: Over here now.

00:34:49.990 --> 00:34:51.739
DAN GALPIN: There's
two out there, I know.

00:34:51.739 --> 00:34:55.170
It's the blue one.

00:34:55.170 --> 00:34:58.410
AUDIENCE: We are in the
progress of integrating

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:01.000
real-time multiplayer
in our game,

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.305
and we have some pretty
detailed stuff, where

00:35:03.305 --> 00:35:06.190
we have some issues how
to solve some problems.

00:35:06.190 --> 00:35:09.360
And we're not sure whether
the API supports them.

00:35:09.360 --> 00:35:12.460
Where would you recommend
we go to find questions

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:14.300
to such detailed questions?

00:35:14.300 --> 00:35:16.060
DAN GALPIN: So there's
kind of two things.

00:35:16.060 --> 00:35:20.290
One is that Stack Overflow is
actually our primary support

00:35:20.290 --> 00:35:21.820
site for Play Games Services.

00:35:21.820 --> 00:35:23.320
We actually have out own tag.

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:26.370
So that's certainly a
great place to start.

00:35:26.370 --> 00:35:28.090
Obviously, you know
people at Google.

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:30.001
You can also ask us.

00:35:30.001 --> 00:35:31.750
If Stack Overflow
doesn't have the answer,

00:35:31.750 --> 00:35:33.250
you can always ask
another question.

00:35:33.250 --> 00:35:36.330
We actually do try to monitor
that on a semi-regular basis

00:35:36.330 --> 00:35:37.030
as well.

00:35:37.030 --> 00:35:41.160
But since you know us, you can
certainly ask us as directly.

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:45.150
While you're here, just
find one of us afterwards.

00:35:45.150 --> 00:35:48.330
AUDIENCE: That would mean,
if I make a question on Stack

00:35:48.330 --> 00:35:50.750
Overflow, and nobody
answers it, then I

00:35:50.750 --> 00:35:53.240
could send an email to
you and then you would--

00:35:53.240 --> 00:35:54.540
DAN GALPIN: You can actually
send it to both of us

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:55.280
at the same time.

00:35:55.280 --> 00:35:56.000
That works, too.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:57.749
You could say, I just
posted this question

00:35:57.749 --> 00:35:59.640
on Stack Overflow, link.

00:35:59.640 --> 00:36:00.350
Can you help?

00:36:00.350 --> 00:36:04.760
And I'll make sure to send
it to someone on our team who

00:36:04.760 --> 00:36:06.967
might be able to
answer that question.

00:36:06.967 --> 00:36:08.550
But I really like
using Stack Overflow

00:36:08.550 --> 00:36:09.780
because I like
making sure that once

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:12.040
we give out an answer, as
many people as possible

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:13.289
can get access to that answer.

00:36:13.289 --> 00:36:15.139
So unless it's
something proprietary,

00:36:15.139 --> 00:36:16.180
it's be great to do that.

00:36:16.180 --> 00:36:17.221
To go through that route.

00:36:19.930 --> 00:36:22.420
AUDIENCE: I just wondered
what the economics are

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:25.950
for using this new
cross-platform multiplayer.

00:36:25.950 --> 00:36:28.080
Like, how much
does that cost us?

00:36:28.080 --> 00:36:30.230
DAN GALPIN: All these
services are all free.

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:33.190
They have generous quotas.

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:36.289
If for some reason those
quotas aren't good enough,

00:36:36.289 --> 00:36:36.830
just tell us.

00:36:36.830 --> 00:36:38.050
We'll give you more quota.

00:36:38.050 --> 00:36:41.400
We just need to know why our
services are getting picked on.

00:36:41.400 --> 00:36:42.500
I didn't mention that.

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:44.945
Yeah, like all this
stuff, we're providing

00:36:44.945 --> 00:36:46.320
all this infrastructure
for free.

00:36:46.320 --> 00:36:48.160
We want to actually
improve games.

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:52.780
We see a lot of upside to games
being better and more engaging,

00:36:52.780 --> 00:36:55.010
with a stronger player pool.

00:36:55.010 --> 00:36:57.332
So that's why we're doing this.

00:36:57.332 --> 00:36:59.665
And we really, really feel
that the cross-platform story

00:36:59.665 --> 00:37:02.994
is very, very important
to our gamers.

00:37:02.994 --> 00:37:04.660
To the most important
people, the people

00:37:04.660 --> 00:37:08.237
who are actually playing games.

00:37:08.237 --> 00:37:09.070
Any other questions?

00:37:11.870 --> 00:37:15.780
AUDIENCE: How is Apple
is reacting to that?

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:19.960
DAN GALPIN: You know, I don't
have any friends at Apple

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:23.550
that have told me anything
negative about it.

00:37:23.550 --> 00:37:29.260
I think that we feel
that this kind of service

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:31.250
is the best thing for users.

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:33.580
And that's the
way we look at it.

00:37:33.580 --> 00:37:38.120
It's kind of a philosophy we
have at Google, in general way,

00:37:38.120 --> 00:37:40.350
is to put our users first.

00:37:40.350 --> 00:37:43.580
That's why we've gone to
such lengths to do this.

00:37:43.580 --> 00:37:45.330
I actually think we're
going to go farther

00:37:45.330 --> 00:37:47.735
in terms of cross-platform
support in the future.

00:37:47.735 --> 00:37:49.980
I mean, right now we
have again, REST APIs.

00:37:49.980 --> 00:37:51.350
That's pretty platform agnostic.

00:37:51.350 --> 00:37:54.075
I'd like to see us even do
one step better than that.

00:37:54.075 --> 00:37:56.200
So hopefully you'll see
more from us in the future.

00:37:56.200 --> 00:37:59.311
But again, this is all about
giving users what they want.

00:37:59.311 --> 00:38:01.310
Which is the ability to
play with their friends.

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:04.350
And for me, the ability to
play on any device I choose.

00:38:04.350 --> 00:38:07.290
Whether or not it's an Android
device or an iOS device

00:38:07.290 --> 00:38:09.754
or even some other device
from another manufacturer.

00:38:09.754 --> 00:38:11.420
And there's no reason
you can't actually

00:38:11.420 --> 00:38:13.586
use these services anywhere
you have REST endpoints.

00:38:18.247 --> 00:38:19.080
RICHARD HYNDMAN: OK?

00:38:19.080 --> 00:38:19.910
DAN GALPIN: All right.

00:38:19.910 --> 00:38:20.840
RICHARD HYNDMAN: Thank
you very much, Dan Galpin.

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:21.890
DAN GALPIN: Thank you.

